[normal]Q164 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Now, if you want to make a brief one-minute opening statement, either of you or both, please feel free before we get on to the questions.
[normal]Rebecca Taylor[bold]: The questions cover pretty much anything I might want to say
[normal],
[normal] so I would just go through the questions.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Okay. Thank you very much indeed.
[normal]Rebecca Taylor[bold]: I will probably give the overview and then Luca will give the detail. The general consensus is that there is a jobs crisis in 
[normal]Europe
[normal] full stop
[normal],
[normal] but that it has been felt far more acutely by young people. Even in those countries where youth unemployment is not such a serious problem, it is still more difficult for under-25s to get a job. There is a lot of concern that if it is not tackled you 
[normal]will 
[normal]get this lost generation thing where if people suffer unemployment or precarious employment for a number of years
[normal], it has 
[normal]a knock-on effect 
[normal]o
[normal]n their long-term career prospects.
[normal]There are a number of things to look at. One is obviously the demand side
[normal]. E
[normal]mployers are simply recruiting 
[normal]fewer workers, 
[normal]and particularly are recruiting 
[normal]fewer 
[normal]young workers, because the less experience you have
[normal],
[normal] the more difficult it is to get into the employment market. That is where it is important to look at incentives that help businesses hire young people
[normal],
[normal] and also obviously incentives that help companies in the right sectors. For example, we had the 
[normal]G
[normal]reen 
[normal]J
[normal]obs initiative in the 
[normal]UK
[normal];
[normal] that is a very good example. It is not willy-nilly. It is really for areas that are considered to have growth potential
[normal],
[normal] because
[normal],
[normal] obviously
[normal],
[normal] if those areas grow there will be more jobs and more jobs for young people. There is also the problem of two-tier labour markets where you have a core of people who are highly protected and young people who just do not get a chance to get that kind of employment protection and end up 
[normal]with work that is 
[normal]either temporary or—
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Seasonal?
[normal]Rebecca Taylor[bold]: Yes, seasonal. I would say freelance
[normal],
[normal] but freelance is something in my mind a little bit different that people choose to do. I know that in 
[normal]Italy
[normal] you have this contract
[normal] called 
[normal]the co
[normal].co.co
[normal].
[normal]Luca Scarpiello[bold]: Yes.
[normal]Rebecca Taylor[bold]: Maybe you can explain what that is.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Right, so 
[normal]this is 
[normal]your statement.
[normal]Luca Scarpiello[bold]: Yes. Well, in Italy the comparison with the UK system is the zero-hour contract, which basically is also now in discussion not only in Italy but all over Europe, because 
[normal]those types of contract 
[normal]have 
[normal]a 
[normal]huge social cost, especially if they are not also match
[normal]ed by 
[normal]reforms 
[normal]to 
[normal]the welfare system that 
[normal]balance 
[normal]the on-call 
[normal]nature of the 
[normal]job 
[normal]with
[normal] the income stability of the person.
[normal]In general, completing what Rebecca was saying, one of the biggest mistakes that we are doing today in Europe is to consider youth employment as something aside from the general employment crisis that we are having in 
[normal]Europe
[normal]. I do not have to remind you of the economic outlook and also 
[normal]of 
[normal]the employment outlook. It is clear that instead this is a part of this outlook and, in general, it is also clear that we will not improve the situation of young people in the labour market unless we are triggering consistent industrial policy, especially at European level, that can support enterprises to invest again and also, of course, to invest in the labour market in human resources.
[normal]When we talk about the special features of young people and their approach to employment, of course, first of all we have to consider that so far they have been—if you see the OECD report on this—the ones that have paid the highest toll in the economic crisis so far. They are also the key potential to trigger a new recovery in 
[normal]Europe
[normal] and also to trigger what we call the ecological conversion of our society, especially if you consider that we are talking about the most skilled generation ever.
[normal]Rebecca Taylor[bold]: The whole green jobs agenda, yes.
[normal]Luca Scarpiello[bold]: When it comes to the actions that we could take in the labour market, also completing what Rebecca was saying, it is important to consider three main dimensions that are fundamental.
[normal]The first one is the demand side. Because we have a number of structural barriers to youth employment today in Europe, and also in the UK, of course, starting from the consideration that the crisis has de
[normal]graded
[normal] the productive manufacturing fabric and this 
[normal]has 
[normal]delayed the investment and employment of new human resources, it is, therefore, fundamental to stimulate the industrial and productive system, especially in the more innovative technologies. Investment in the more innovative technologies is today also a way to fight youth unemployment.
[normal]The second is, of course, that in Europe—and this is a shared problem 
[normal]with 
[normal]the 
[normal]UK
[normal]—we have a strong duality and segmentation of the labour market. It is a matter of fact that young people today are the most exposed to the problems 
[normal]of 
[normal]stability 
[normal]in 
[normal]the labour market, the first ones to be dismissed, and the last ones to be hired. For this
[normal],
[normal] a reference for you could be the OECD employment index for regular contracts. We have seen that in the past the legislation when it comes especially to hiring for temporary contracts—we have seen in the UK the zero
[normal]-hours
[normal] contract—did not have an impact on the hiring preparation of the enterprises. This is not an opinion; this is a fact that was put together by the OECD in the last 
[normal]E
[normal]conomic 
[normal]O
[normal]utlook
[normal]. Therefore, when it comes to reducing the barriers, the priority should be to reduce the segmentation especially between temporary and stable contracts and try to reduce the gap in a way.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Yes, that is the detail. Overall, would 
[normal]you 
[normal]agree that it is 
[normal]probably 
[normal]the most difficult problem facing the European Union at the moment?
[normal]Luca Scarpiello[bold]: Absolutely.
