[normal]Q166 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] 
[normal]To what extent do you see the issue as being about the demand side, the availability of jobs, and to what extent the supply side, how well young people are prepared for the labour market with regard to their skills or employability?
[normal]Rebecca Taylor[bold]: It is both, really. There was rising youth unemployment previously, certainly in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] when there was a boom, and that was among a certain section of the population. Graduates were not included in that, for example, so 
[normal]it 
[normal]was a skills issue. The youth unemployment now is not just those with lower skills. It is graduates as well
[normal]. I
[normal]n my day—I graduated in 1997—it was almost impossible not to get a job. The only people who did not get a job were people who really did not want one. A friend of mine tried being unemployed for a few months but he gave up because it was easier to find a job. Seriously, he just wanted a rest. He had worked so hard for his exams; he just wanted a rest.
[normal]It is a very different situation now. I have a stepbrother and it has taken him a year to find a job. He has been cleaning a pub. He is a maths graduate and he has been cleaning a pub. He has an appropriate job now, but he was prepared to do anything in order to work. That is something that when I graduated in 1997 would have been almost unheard of. Obviously, it is much more difficult for people who do not have qualifications, but that does not mean that it is necessarily easy because we have the problem of graduate unemployment, which existed already in a number of European countries before the crisis. You ha
[normal]ve
[normal] problems that did not happen, for example, in the 
[normal]UK
[normal], in 
[normal]Germany
[normal], in the 
[normal]Netherlands
[normal]. There are the OECD recommendations, which are aimed less, I would say, at the skilled or highly educated employees 
[normal]and more at 
[normal]minimising school drop-out, promoting a combination of work and study, which is what we are having in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] now with the apprenticeships, and offering people a second chance to get a qualification.
[normal]Q167 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] What role should different stakeholders play in tackling youth unemployment—for example, the Commission, national Governments, businesses or trade unions—and how does the work of the Youth Intergroup feed into this dialogue?
[normal]Rebecca Taylor[bold]: Yes. Well, obviously, this is something that cannot come 
[normal]only 
